<BaseLayout title="Decision Framing">
  <h1>Decision Framing</h1>
  <p class="muted">Early-stage transaction definition</p>

  <p>
    Decision Framing is conducted before a capital commitment is fully formed.
    A transaction may be advancing, terms may be circulating,
    but the commitment boundary has not yet been written down.
  </p>

  <p>
    The session defines the decision in one sentence,
    lists embedded assumptions,
    and identifies where downside would sit if those assumptions fail.
  </p>

  <h2>When to Use</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Internal disagreement about whether to proceed</li>
    <li>Unclear downside allocation during structuring</li>
    <li>Timing pressure compressing risk assessment</li>
    <li>Informal commitments forming before formal review</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Output</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>One-sentence decision definition</li>
    <li>List of embedded assumptions</li>
    <li>Initial downside mapping</li>
    <li>Required open items before advancement</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Engagement Structure</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Single defined decision or transaction</li>
    <li>90-minute session</li>
    <li>Written summary delivered within 24 hours</li>
  </ul>

